Differential TAD Analysis

0.1 Loading Libraries

Once you have .hic files from HiCFlow pipeline, you can perform differential TAD analysis using TADCompare. The tutorial shown below gives you a sneakpeak on how to navigate the waters.

library(strawr)
library(TADCompare)
library(dplyr)
library(ggeasy)
library(ggplot2)

0.2 Reading .hic files and combining the replicates

To read the .hic files, we will use strawr. We will merge biological replicates by simply summing up their counts (see discussion here).

setwd("~/data/coursework2024/exam/plasmodium_results/04_juicerResults")
files <- list.files(pattern = "_30.hic", recursive = TRUE)
chrs <- read.table("../chrlist")[,1]
# Converting chromosomes to upper case because that's how strawr likes it.
chrs <- toupper(chrs)

chrs

## Tads at 50K resolution
p40hpi.ko.rep2 <- lapply(chrs, function(x){
  strawr::straw("NONE", "SRR19611534/inter_30.hic", x, x, "BP", 50000)  
})
p40hpi.ko.rep1 <- lapply(chrs, function(x){
  strawr::straw("NONE", "SRR19611535/inter_30.hic", x, x, "BP", 50000)  
})

## combine TADS
ko40 <- lapply(1:14, function(x){
  #ConsensusTADs(list(p40hpi.ko.rep2[[x]],p40hpi.ko.rep1[[x]]), resolution = 50000)
  ## merging the replicates
  bind_rows(p40hpi.ko.rep2[[x]],p40hpi.ko.rep1[[x]]) %>% group_by(x,y) %>% summarise(counts = sum(counts), .groups = 'drop') 
  
})

0.3 Comparing TADS

Use TADCompare function to now perform differential TAD analysis. The TAD boundaries can be classified into 5 types (see figure below):

0.3.1 Boundary Changes Categorization:

Categories of Boundary Changes: These 5 categories include: 1. Complex 2. Split 3. Merge 4. Shifted 5. Strength Change

  1. Split:
    • An interacting domain can exist as a continuous domain in one dataset and split into two or more domains in another.
    • Requires two shared boundaries and a differential domain between them.
  2. Merge:
    • Merging is the opposite of splitting.
    • Occurs when a boundary between two non-differential boundaries disappears in one of the contact matrices.
  3. Complex:
    • Domains can also be modified in a complex way, meaning they neither split nor merge but instead adopt a completely new structure.
    • Complex boundaries are considered part of a different domain.

Complex, merge, and split boundaries represent the most disruptive changes in the 3D genome structure. - Merged and Split Boundaries: Represent structural changes within the same domain. - Complex Boundaries: Considered a part of an entirely different domain.

  1. Shifted:
    • Defined as non-overlapping boundaries within five bins (or another user-defined threshold) of a boundary in the reference contact matrix.
  2. Strength Changes:
    • Occur when a boundary is present in both contact matrices, but its differential boundary score magnitude exceeds a differential threshold of 2.

Non-Differential Boundaries: - Boundaries not fitting into the above categories are considered non-differential boundaries.

#Performing differential TAD analysis for all chromosomes 
p16hpi<-lapply(1:14, function(x){
  TADCompare(ko16[[x]], ctrl16[[x]], resolution=50000)})

plts<-lapply(1:14, function(x){
  df<-data.frame(table(p16hpi[[x]]$TAD_Frame$Type))
  ggplot(df,aes(Var1,Freq,col=Var1, fill=Var1))+geom_bar(stat = "identity",position="stack")+theme_minimal()+ scale_fill_manual(values=c("Non-Differential"="#E64B35B2","Complex"="#4DBBD5B2","Shifted"="#00A087B2","Strength Change"="#3C5488B2","Merge"="#F39B7FB2"))+
    scale_color_manual(values=c("Non-Differential"="#E64B35B2","Complex"="#4DBBD5B2","Shifted"="#00A087B2","Strength Change"="#3C5488B2","Merge"="#F39B7FB2"))+easy_remove_x_axis(what = c("ticks","text"))+coord_fixed(ratio = 3)+ylab("No. of Boundaries")+xlab(chrs[x])+easy_add_legend_title("")
  })
